[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] In this form of Bézout's identity, there is no denominator in the formula.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] If one divides everything by the resultant one gets the classical Bézout's identity, with an explicit common denominator for the rational numbers that appear in it.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] To implement the algorithm that is described above, one should first remark that only the two last values of the indexed variables are needed at each step.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Thus, for saving memory, each indexed variable must be replaced by just two variables.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] For simplicity, the following algorithm (and the other algorithms in this article) uses parallel assignments.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] In a programming language which does not have this feature, the parallel assignments need to be simulated with an auxiliary variable.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] and similarly for the other parallel assignments.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] The quotients of *a* and *b* by their greatest common divisor, which is output, may have an incorrect sign.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] This is easy to correct at the end of the computation but has not been done here for simplifying the code.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Similarly, if either *a* or *b* is zero and the other is negative, the greatest common divisor that is output is negative, and all the signs of the output must be changed.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Finally, notice that in Bézout's identity, $ax+by=\gcd(a,b)$ , one can solve for y given $a,b,x,\gcd(a,b)$ .
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] When using integers of unbounded size, the time needed for multiplication and division grows quadratically with the size of the integers.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] This implies that the "optimisation" replaces a sequence of multiplications/divisions of small integers by a single multiplication/division, which requires more computing time than the operations that it replaces, taken together.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] A fraction ⁠*a*/*b*⁠ is in canonical simplified form if *a* and *b* are coprime and *b* is positive.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] The proof of this algorithm relies on the fact that *s* and *t* are two coprime integers such that *as* + *bt* = 0, and thus ${\frac {a}{b}}=-{\frac {t}{s}}$ .
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] To get the canonical simplified form, it suffices to move the minus sign for having a positive denominator.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] If *b* divides *a* evenly, the algorithm executes only one iteration, and we have *s* = 1 at the end of the algorithm.
