[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] The extended Euclidean algorithm is the essential tool for computing multiplicative inverses in modular structures, typically the modular integers and the algebraic field extensions.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] A notable instance of the latter case are the finite fields of non-prime order.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] If *n* is a positive integer, the ring **Z**/*n***Z** may be identified with the set {0, 1, ..., *n*-1} of the remainders of Euclidean division by *n*, the addition and the multiplication consisting in taking the remainder by *n* of the result of the addition and the multiplication of integers.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] An element *a* of **Z**/*n***Z** has a multiplicative inverse (that is, it is a unit) if it is coprime to *n*.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] In particular, if *n* is prime, *a* has a multiplicative inverse if it is not zero (modulo *n*).
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Thus **Z**/*n***Z** is a field if and only if *n* is prime.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Thus *t*, or, more exactly, the remainder of the division of *t* by *n*, is the multiplicative inverse of *a* modulo *n*.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] To adapt the extended Euclidean algorithm to this problem, one should remark that the Bézout coefficient of *n* is not needed, and thus does not need to be computed.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Also, for getting a result which is positive and lower than *n*, one may use the fact that the integer *t* provided by the algorithm satisfies |*t*| < *n*.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] That is, if *t* < 0, one must add *n* to it at the end (an example can be found in the article Modular multiplicative inverse).
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] This results in the pseudocode, in which the input *n* is an integer larger than 1.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] The extended Euclidean algorithm is also the main tool for computing multiplicative inverses in simple algebraic field extensions.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] An important case, widely used in cryptography and coding theory, is that of finite fields of non-prime order.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] In fact, if *p* is a prime number, and *q* = *p**d*, the field of order *q* is a simple algebraic extension of the prime field of *p* elements, generated by a root of an irreducible polynomial of degree *d*.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] A simple algebraic extension *L* of a field *K*, generated by the root of an irreducible polynomial *p* of degree *d* may be identified to the quotient ring $K[X]/\langle p\rangle ,$ , and its elements are in bijective correspondence with the polynomials of degree less than *d*.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] The addition in *L* is the addition of polynomials.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] The multiplication in *L* is the remainder of the Euclidean division by *p* of the product of polynomials.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Thus, to complete the arithmetic in *L*, it remains only to define how to compute multiplicative inverses.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] This is done by the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] The algorithm is very similar to that provided above for computing the modular multiplicative inverse.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] There are two main differences: firstly the last but one line is not needed, because the Bézout coefficient that is provided always has a degree less than *d*.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Secondly, the greatest common divisor which is provided, when the input polynomials are coprime, may be any nonzero element of *K*; this Bézout coefficient (a polynomial generally of positive degree) has thus to be multiplied by the inverse of this element of *K*.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] In the pseudocode which follows, *p* is a polynomial of degree greater than one, and *a* is a polynomial.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] For example, if the polynomial used to define the finite field GF(28) is *p* = *x*8 + *x*4 + *x*3 + *x* + 1, and *a* = *x*6 + *x*4 + *x* + 1 is the element whose inverse is desired, then performing the algorithm results in the computation described in the following table.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Let us recall that in fields of order 2*n*, one has −*z* = *z* and *z* + *z* = 0 for every element *z* in the field).
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Since 1 is the only nonzero element of GF(2), the adjustment in the last line of the pseudocode is not needed.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Thus, the inverse is *x*7 + *x*6 + *x*3 + *x*, as can be confirmed by multiplying the two elements together, and taking the remainder by p of the result.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] One can handle the case of more than two numbers iteratively.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] By definition of gcd d is a divisor of a and b .
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] Similarly d is a divisor of c so $c=jd$ for some j .
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] By our construction of u , $ud|a,b,c$ but since d is the greatest divisor u is a unit.
[src:extended-euclidean/extended-euclidean-algorithm] And since $ud=\gcd(\gcd(a,b),c)$ the result is proven.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] In mathematics, the **greatest common divisor** (**GCD**), also known as **greatest common factor (GCF)**, of two or more integers, which are not all zero, is the largest positive integer that divides each of the integers.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] For two integers *x*, *y*, the greatest common divisor of *x* and *y* is denoted $\gcd(x,y)$ .
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] For example, the GCD of 8 and 12 is 4, that is, gcd(8, 12) = 4.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] In the name "greatest common divisor", the adjective "greatest" may be replaced by "highest", and the word "divisor" may be replaced by "factor", so that other names include **highest common factor (HCF)**, etc.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Historically, other names for the same concept have included **greatest common measure**.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This notion can be extended to polynomials (see *Polynomial greatest common divisor*) and other commutative rings (see *§ In commutative rings* below).
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The *greatest common divisor* (GCD) of integers a and b, at least one of which is nonzero, is the greatest positive integer d such that d is a divisor of both a and b; that is, there are integers e and f such that *a* = *de* and *b* = *df*, and d is the largest such integer.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The GCD of a and b is generally denoted gcd(*a*, *b*).
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] When one of *a* and *b* is zero, the GCD is the absolute value of the nonzero integer: gcd(*a*, 0) = gcd(0, *a*) = |*a*|.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This case is important as the terminating step of the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The above definition is unsuitable for defining gcd(0, 0), since there is no greatest integer *n* such that 0 × *n* = 0.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] However, zero is its own greatest divisor if *greatest* is understood in the context of the divisibility relation, so gcd(0, 0) is commonly defined as 0.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This preserves the usual identities for GCD, and in particular Bézout's identity, namely that gcd(*a*, *b*) generates the same ideal as {*a*, *b*}.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This convention is followed by many computer algebra systems.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Nonetheless, some authors leave gcd(0, 0) undefined.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The GCD of a and b is their greatest positive common divisor in the preorder relation of divisibility.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This means that the common divisors of a and b are exactly the divisors of their GCD.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This is commonly proved by using either Euclid's lemma, the fundamental theorem of arithmetic, or the Euclidean algorithm.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This is the meaning of "greatest" that is used for the generalizations of the concept of GCD.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Computing all divisors of the two numbers in this way is usually not efficient, especially for large numbers that have many divisors.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Much more efficient methods are described in *§ Calculation*.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Two numbers are called relatively prime, or coprime, if their greatest common divisor equals 1.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] For example, a 24-by-60 rectangular area can be divided into a grid of: 1-by-1 squares, 2-by-2 squares, 3-by-3 squares, 4-by-4 squares, 6-by-6 squares or 12-by-12 squares.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Therefore, 12 is the greatest common divisor of 24 and 60.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] A 24-by-60 rectangular area can thus be divided into a grid of 12-by-12 squares, with two squares along one edge (24/12 = 2) and five squares along the other (60/12 = 5).
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The greatest common divisor is useful for reducing fractions to the lowest terms.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Greatest common divisors can be computed by determining the prime factorizations of the two numbers and comparing factors.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] In practice, this method is only feasible for small numbers, as computing prime factorizations takes too long.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The method introduced by Euclid for computing greatest common divisors is based on the fact that, given two positive integers a and b such that *a* > *b*, the common divisors of a and b are the same as the common divisors of *a* – *b* and b.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] So, Euclid's method for computing the greatest common divisor of two positive integers consists of replacing the larger number with the difference of the numbers, and repeating this until the two numbers are equal: that is their greatest common divisor.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This method can be very slow if one number is much larger than the other.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] So, the variant that follows is generally preferred.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] A more efficient method is the *Euclidean algorithm*, a variant in which the difference of the two numbers a and b is replaced by the *remainder* of the Euclidean division (also called *division with remainder*) of a by b.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Denoting this remainder as *a* mod *b*, the algorithm replaces (*a*, *b*) with (*b*, *a* mod *b*) repeatedly until the pair is (*d*, 0), where d is the greatest common divisor.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The binary GCD algorithm is a variant of Euclid's algorithm that is specially adapted to the binary representation of the numbers, which is used in most computers.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The binary GCD algorithm differs from Euclid's algorithm essentially by dividing by two every even number that is encountered during the computation.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Its efficiency results from the fact that, in binary representation, testing parity consists of testing the right-most digit, and dividing by two consists of removing the right-most digit.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The method is as follows, starting with *a* and *b* that are the two positive integers whose GCD is sought.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] If *a* is even, then divide it by two until it becomes odd.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] If *b* is even, then divide it by two until it becomes odd.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Step 1 determines d as the highest power of 2 that divides *a* and *b*, and thus their greatest common divisor.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] None of the steps changes the set of the odd common divisors of *a* and *b*.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This shows that when the algorithm stops, the result is correct.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The algorithm stops eventually, since each steps divides at least one of the operands by at least 2.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Moreover, the number of divisions by 2 and thus the number of subtractions is at most the total number of digits.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The binary GCD algorithm is particularly easy to implement and particularly efficient on binary computers.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The square in this complexity comes from the fact that division by 2 and subtraction take a time that is proportional to the number of bits of the input.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The computational complexity is usually given in terms of the length *n* of the input.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Lehmer's algorithm is based on the observation that the initial quotients produced by Euclid's algorithm can be determined based on only the first few digits; this is useful for numbers that are larger than a computer word.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] In essence, one extracts initial digits, typically forming one or two computer words, and runs Euclid's algorithms on these smaller numbers, as long as it is guaranteed that the quotients are the same with those that would be obtained with the original numbers.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The quotients are collected into a small 2-by-2 transformation matrix (a matrix of single-word integers) to reduce the original numbers.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This process is repeated until numbers are small enough that the binary algorithm (see below) is more efficient.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This algorithm improves speed, because it reduces the number of operations on very large numbers, and can use hardware arithmetic for most operations.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] In fact, most of the quotients are very small, so a fair number of steps of the Euclidean algorithm can be collected in a 2-by-2 matrix of single-word integers.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] When Lehmer's algorithm encounters a quotient that is too large, it must fall back to one iteration of Euclidean algorithm, with a Euclidean division of large numbers.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] but more commonly the LCM is computed from the GCD.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] which generalizes to *a* and *b* rational numbers or commensurable real numbers.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] which is a function that can be evaluated for complex *b*.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] is an entire function in the variable *b* for all positive integers *a* where *c**d*(*k*) is Ramanujan's sum.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The computational complexity of the computation of greatest common divisors has been widely studied.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] If one uses the Euclidean algorithm and the elementary algorithms for multiplication and division, the computation of the greatest common divisor of two integers of at most n bits is *O*(*n*2).
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This means that the computation of greatest common divisor has, up to a constant factor, the same complexity as the multiplication.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] However, if a fast multiplication algorithm is used, one may modify the Euclidean algorithm for improving the complexity, but the computation of a greatest common divisor becomes slower than the multiplication.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] More precisely, if the multiplication of two integers of *n* bits takes a time of *T*(*n*), then the fastest known algorithm for greatest common divisor has a complexity *O*(*T*(*n*) log *n*).
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This implies that the fastest known algorithm has a complexity of *O*(*n* (log *n*)2).
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Previous complexities are valid for the usual models of computation, specifically multitape Turing machines and random-access machines.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The computation of the greatest common divisors belongs thus to the class of problems solvable in quasilinear time.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] *A fortiori*, the corresponding decision problem belongs to the class P of problems solvable in polynomial time.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The GCD problem is not known to be in NC, and so there is no known way to parallelize it efficiently; nor is it known to be P-complete, which would imply that it is unlikely to be possible to efficiently parallelize GCD computation.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Shallcross et al. showed that a related problem (EUGCD, determining the remainder sequence arising during the Euclidean algorithm) is NC-equivalent to the problem of integer linear programming with two variables; if either problem is in **NC** or is **P-complete**, the other is as well.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Since **NC** contains NL, it is also unknown whether a space-efficient algorithm for computing the GCD exists, even for nondeterministic Turing machines.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Although the problem is not known to be in **NC**, parallel algorithms asymptotically faster than the Euclidean algorithm exist; the fastest known deterministic algorithm is by Chor and Goldreich, which (in the CRCW-PRAM model) can solve the problem in *O*(*n*/log *n*) time with *n*1+*ε* processors.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Randomized algorithms can solve the problem in *O*((log *n*)2) time on $O\left(e^{\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)$ processors (this is superpolynomial).
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This formula is often used to compute least common multiples: one first computes the GCD with Euclid's algorithm and then divides the product of the given numbers by their GCD.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Nymann showed that *k* integers, chosen independently and uniformly from {1, ..., *n*}, are coprime with probability 1/*ζ*(*k*) as *n* goes to infinity, where *ζ* refers to the Riemann zeta function.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] (See coprime for a derivation.) This result was extended in 1987 to show that the probability that *k* random integers have greatest common divisor *d* is *d*−*k*/ζ(*k*).
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Using this information, the expected value of the greatest common divisor function can be seen (informally) to not exist when *k* = 2.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This last summation is the harmonic series, which diverges.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] For *k* = 3, this is approximately equal to 1.3684.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The notion of greatest common divisor can more generally be defined for elements of an arbitrary commutative ring, although in general there need not exist one for every pair of elements.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] With this definition, two elements a and b may very well have several greatest common divisors, or none at all.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] If R is an integral domain, then any two GCDs of a and b must be associate elements, since by definition either one must divide the other.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Indeed, if a GCD exists, any one of its associates is a GCD as well.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Existence of a GCD is not assured in arbitrary integral domains.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] However, if R is a unique factorization domain or any other GCD domain, then any two elements have a GCD.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] The elements 2 and $1+{\sqrt {-3}}$ are two maximal common divisors (that is, any common divisor which is a multiple of 2 is associated to 2, the same holds for $1+{\sqrt {-3}}$ , but they are not associated, so there is no greatest common divisor of a and *b*.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] Corresponding to the Bézout property we may, in any commutative ring, consider the collection of elements of the form *pa* + *qb*, where p and q range over the ring.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] This is the ideal generated by a and b, and is denoted simply (*a*, *b*).
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] In a ring all of whose ideals are principal (a principal ideal domain or PID), this ideal will be identical with the set of multiples of some ring element *d*; then this d is a greatest common divisor of a and *b*.
[src:extended-euclidean/greatest-common-divisor] But the ideal (*a*, *b*) can be useful even when there is no greatest common divisor of a and *b*.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In mathematics, particularly in the area of arithmetic, a **modular multiplicative inverse** of an integer a is an integer x such that the product ax is congruent to 1 with respect to the modulus m.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] which is the shorthand way of writing the statement that m divides (evenly) the quantity *ax* − 1, or, put another way, the remainder after dividing ax by the integer m is 1.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] If a does have an inverse modulo m, then there is an infinite number of solutions of this congruence, which form a congruence class with respect to this modulus.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Furthermore, any integer that is congruent to a (i.e., in a's congruence class) has any element of x's congruence class as a modular multiplicative inverse.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] where the symbol $\cdot$ denotes the multiplication of equivalence classes modulo m.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Written in this way, the analogy with the usual concept of a multiplicative inverse in the set of rational or real numbers is clearly represented, replacing the numbers by congruence classes and altering the binary operation appropriately.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Finding modular multiplicative inverses also has practical applications in the field of cryptography, e.g. public-key cryptography and the RSA algorithm.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] A benefit for the computer implementation of these applications is that there exists a very fast algorithm (the extended Euclidean algorithm) that can be used for the calculation of modular multiplicative inverses.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] For a given positive integer m, two integers, a and b, are said to be **congruent modulo m** if m divides their difference.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] This is an equivalence relation on the set of integers, $\mathbb {Z}$ , and the equivalence classes are called **congruence classes modulo m** or **residue classes modulo m**.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Unlike linear equations over the reals, linear congruences may have zero, one or several solutions.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] If x is a solution of a linear congruence then every element in ${\overline {x}}$ is also a solution, so, when speaking of the number of solutions of a linear congruence we are referring to the number of different congruence classes that contain solutions.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] If d is the greatest common divisor of a and m then the linear congruence *ax* ≡ *b* (mod *m*) has solutions if and only if d divides b.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] If d divides b, then there are exactly d solutions.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The previous result says that a solution exists if and only if gcd(*a*, *m*) = 1, that is, a and m must be relatively prime (i.e. coprime).
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] If *a* ≡ 0 (mod *m*), then gcd(*a*, *m*) = *m*, and a won't even have a modular multiplicative inverse.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] but this can be considered an abuse of notation since it could be misinterpreted as the reciprocal of a (which, contrary to the modular multiplicative inverse, is not an integer except when a is 1 or −1).
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The notation would be proper if a is interpreted as a token standing for the congruence class ${\overline {a}}$ , as the multiplicative inverse of a congruence class is a congruence class with the multiplication defined in the next section.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The congruence relation, modulo m, partitions the set of integers into m congruence classes.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] where + and $\,\!\cdot$ on the left denote addition and multiplication of congruence classes modulo m.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] These operations are well-defined, meaning that the end result does not depend on the choices of representatives that were made to obtain the result.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The m congruence classes with these two defined operations form a commutative ring, called the **ring of integers modulo m**.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] There are several notations used for these algebraic objects, most often $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ or $\mathbb {Z} /m$ , but several elementary texts and application areas use a simplified notation $\mathbb {Z} _{m}$ when confusion with other algebraic objects is unlikely.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The congruence classes of the integers modulo m were traditionally known as *residue classes modulo m*, reflecting the fact that all the elements of a congruence class have the same remainder (i.e., "residue") upon being divided by m.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Any set of m integers selected so that each comes from a different congruence class modulo m is called a **complete system of residues modulo m**.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The division algorithm shows that the set of integers, {0, 1, 2, ..., *m* − 1} form a complete system of residues modulo m, known as the **least residue system modulo m**.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In working with arithmetic problems it is sometimes more convenient to work with a complete system of residues and use the language of congruences while at other times the point of view of the congruence classes of the ring $\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z}$ is more useful.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Not every element of a complete residue system modulo m has a modular multiplicative inverse, for instance, zero does not have one if *m* > 1.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] After removing the elements of a complete residue system that are not relatively prime to m, what is left is called a **reduced residue system**, all of whose elements have modular multiplicative inverses.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The number of elements in a reduced residue system is $\phi (m)$ , where $\phi$ is the Euler totient function, i.e., the number of positive integers less than m that are relatively prime to m.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In a general ring with unity not every element has a multiplicative inverse and those that do are called **units**.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] As the product of two units is a unit, the units of a ring form a group, the **group of units of the ring** and often denoted by *R*× if R is the name of the ring.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The group of units of the ring of integers modulo m is called the **multiplicative group of integers modulo m**, and it is isomorphic to a reduced residue system.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In particular, it has order (size), $\phi (m)$ .
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In the case that m is a prime, say p, then $\phi (p)=p-1$ and all the non-zero elements of $\mathbb {Z} /p\mathbb {Z}$ have multiplicative inverses, thus $\mathbb {Z} /p\mathbb {Z}$ is a finite field.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In this case, the multiplicative group of integers modulo p form a cyclic group of order *p* − 1.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] For any integer $n>1$ , it's always the case that $n^{2}-n+1$ is the modular multiplicative inverse of $n+1$ with respect to the modulus $n^{2}$ , since $(n+1)(n^{2}-n+1)=n^{3}+1$ .
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The linear congruence 4*x* ≡ 5 (mod 10) has no solutions since the integers that are congruent to 5 (i.e., those in ${\overline {5}}$ ) are all odd while 4*x* is always even.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] However, the linear congruence 4*x* ≡ 6 (mod 10) has two solutions, namely, *x* = 4 and *x* = 9.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The gcd(4, 10) = 2 and 2 does not divide 5, but does divide 6.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Since gcd(3, 10) = 1, the linear congruence 3*x* ≡ 1 (mod 10) will have solutions, that is, modular multiplicative inverses of 3 modulo 10 will exist.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In fact, 7 satisfies this congruence (i.e., 21 − 1 = 20).
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] However, other integers also satisfy the congruence, for instance 17 and −3 (i.e., 3(17) − 1 = 50 and 3(−3) − 1 = −10).
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] This congruence has only this one congruence class of solutions.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The solution in this case could have been obtained by checking all possible cases, but systematic algorithms would be needed for larger moduli and these will be given in the next section.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The product of congruence classes ${\overline {5}}$ and ${\overline {8}}$ can be obtained by selecting an element of ${\overline {5}}$ , say 25, and an element of ${\overline {8}}$ , say −2, and observing that their product (25)(−2) = −50 is in the congruence class ${\overline {0}}$ .
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The ten congruence classes together with these operations of addition and multiplication of congruence classes form the ring of integers modulo 10, i.e., $\mathbb {Z} /10\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] A complete residue system modulo 10 can be the set {10, −9, 2, 13, 24, −15, 26, 37, 8, 9} where each integer is in a different congruence class modulo 10.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The unique least residue system modulo 10 is {0, 1, 2, ..., 9}.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] A reduced residue system modulo 10 could be {1, 3, 7, 9}.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The product of any two congruence classes represented by these numbers is again one of these four congruence classes.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] This implies that these four congruence classes form a group, in this case the cyclic group of order four, having either 3 or 7 as a (multiplicative) generator.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The represented congruence classes form the group of units of the ring $\mathbb {Z} /10\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] These congruence classes are precisely the ones which have modular multiplicative inverses.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] A modular multiplicative inverse of a modulo m can be found by using the extended Euclidean algorithm.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The Euclidean algorithm determines the greatest common divisor (gcd) of two integers, say a and m.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] If a has a multiplicative inverse modulo m, this gcd must be 1.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The last of several equations produced by the algorithm may be solved for this gcd.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Then, using a method called "back substitution", an expression connecting the original parameters and this gcd can be obtained.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] so, a modular multiplicative inverse of a has been calculated.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] A more efficient version of the algorithm is the extended Euclidean algorithm, which, by using auxiliary equations, reduces two passes through the algorithm (back substitution can be thought of as passing through the algorithm in reverse) to just one.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In big O notation, this algorithm runs in time O(log2(*m*)), assuming |*a*| < *m*, and is considered to be very fast and generally more efficient than its alternative, exponentiation.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In the corresponding table far right with the analogous row operations, one could apparently omit the m -column.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] As an alternative to the extended Euclidean algorithm, Euler's theorem may be used to compute modular inverses.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] where $\phi$ is Euler's totient function.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] This follows from the fact that a belongs to the multiplicative group $(\mathbb {Z} /m\mathbb {Z} )$ × if and only if a is coprime to m.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] This method is generally slower than the extended Euclidean algorithm, but is sometimes used when an implementation for modular exponentiation is already available.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] One notable *advantage* of this technique is that there are no conditional branches which depend on the value of a, and thus the value of a, which may be an important secret in public-key cryptography, can be protected from side-channel attacks.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] For this reason, the standard implementation of Curve25519 uses this technique to compute an inverse.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] It is possible to compute the inverse of multiple numbers ai, modulo a common m, with a single invocation of the Euclidean algorithm and three multiplications per additional input.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The basic idea is to form the product of all the ai, invert that, then multiply by aj for all *j* ≠ *i* to leave only the desired *a*−1 *i*.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Compute *b*−1 *n* using any available algorithm.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] It is possible to perform the multiplications in a tree structure rather than linearly to exploit parallel computing.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In the case where the modulus M is on the form $p^{m}$ for some prime number p and positive integer m, it is possible to compute modular multiplicative inverses efficiently by using the Newton-Raphson iteration, allowing the inverse to be computed with $O(\log m)$ multiplications.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] A practical use of this method is to efficiently compute modular multiplicative inverses modulo powers of 2.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] and then iteratively use Newton-Raphson iterations to compute the modular inverse modulo $2^{6}$ , $2^{12}$ , $2^{24}$ and so on.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Finding a modular multiplicative inverse has many applications in algorithms that rely on the theory of modular arithmetic.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] For instance, in cryptography the use of modular arithmetic permits some operations to be carried out more quickly and with fewer storage requirements, while other operations become more difficult.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Both of these features can be used to advantage.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] In particular, in the RSA algorithm, encrypting and decrypting a message is done using a pair of numbers that are multiplicative inverses with respect to a carefully selected modulus.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] One of these numbers is made public and can be used in a rapid encryption procedure, while the other, used in the decryption procedure, is kept hidden.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Determining the hidden number from the public number is considered to be computationally infeasible and this is what makes the system work to ensure privacy.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] As another example in a different context, consider the exact division problem in computer science where you have a list of odd word-sized numbers each divisible by *k* and you wish to divide them all by *k*.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] For each number in the list, multiply it by *k*−1 and take the least significant word of the result.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] On many machines, particularly those without hardware support for division, division is a slower operation than multiplication, so this approach can yield a considerable speedup.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] The first step is relatively slow but only needs to be done once.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Modular multiplicative inverses are used to obtain a solution of a system of linear congruences that is guaranteed by the Chinese Remainder Theorem.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] has common solutions since 5,7 and 11 are pairwise coprime.
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] = 6 is the modular multiplicative inverse of 5 × 7 (mod 11).
[src:extended-euclidean/modular-multiplicative-inverse] Also, the modular multiplicative inverse figures prominently in the definition of the Kloosterman sum.
